that the manuscript follows a standard scientific paper format (e.g., Introduction, Related Work, Methodology, Results, Conclusion).\n- **References:** Include a comprehensive list of references, ensuring that all cited works are relevant and up-to-date.\n\n### Final Deliverables:\n\n- A final, polished research proposal document that includes a detailed methodology, dataset selection, metrics definition, and expected outcomes.\n- A draft manuscript based on the refined proposal.\n\n### Next Steps:\n\n- Submit the final research proposal for formal review or presentation.\n- Begin the implementation phase of the research project based on the refined proposal.\n\nBy following these steps, the research proposal will be well-refined and ready for the next phase of the research project.\n"}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can we determine the transfer order of intermediate domains in Continuous Domain Adaptation (CDA) without relying on explicit metadata?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem will significantly enhance the effectiveness of CDA by enabling more accurate and efficient domain adaptation. It will allow models to generalize better across diverse domains, which is critical for applications in medical imaging, battery capacity monitoring, and other real-life scenarios where obtaining labeled data for the target domain is costly or infeasible. This research will advance the field by providing a metadata-free method for domain ordering, potentially leading to more robust and adaptable machine learning models.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "Determining the transfer order of intermediate domains without metadata is challenging due to the complex and often non-linear nature of data distributions. Naive approaches, such as random ordering or simple clustering, may fail to capture the underlying domain continuity and can lead to suboptimal adaptation. Technical obstacles 